      "title": "Possessive Pronouns",
      "intro": "German possessive pronouns change their ending based on the gender of the noun that follows. Feminine and Plural nouns add an '-e' (e.g., meine, deine).",
      "config": {
        "speechSequence": ["c2", "c3"]
      },
      "headers": ["English", "German (M/N)", "German (F/P)"],
      "rows": [
        { "c1": "My", "c2": "Mein", "c3": "Meine" },
        { "c1": "Your (Informal)", "c2": "Dein", "c3": "Deine" },
        { "c1": "His / Its", "c2": "Sein", "c3": "Seine" },
        { "c1": "Her", "c2": "Ihr", "c3": "Ihre" },
        { "c1": "Our", "c2": "Unser", "c3": "Unsere" },
        { "c1": "Your (Plural)", "c2": "Euer", "c3": "Eure" },
        { "c1": "Your (Formal) / Their", "c2": "Ihr", "c3": "Ihre" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "EXPLAINER",
      "title": "The 'W' Trap",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "heading": "Pronunciation Warning",
          "text": "In Wollen, the W sounds like a V (Vollen), and the i in 'Ich will' sounds like 'Vill'. Do not confuse this with the English 'will' (future tense)."
        }
      ]
    },
